# Valgrind memcheck suppressions for the nightly replay job (STAGE8.md 8.5, Р53).
#
# Policy: this file is a liability, not a convenience. The replay harness
# (tests/replay/test_replay) drives the whole libbpf-free userspace pipeline —
# decode -> conn_table -> reassembly -> pg parser -> norm -> metrics/export —
# over the committed fixtures, and it must run *clean* under memcheck: at the
# time this file was written it reports 0 errors and "All heap blocks were
# freed -- no leaks are possible". So there is nothing to suppress from our own
# code, and there must never be: a leak in test_replay is a leak in the code
# the agent runs 24/7, and the nightly job failing on it is the point.
#
# Every entry below must therefore
#   (a) belong to libc / the dynamic loader / the toolchain, never to latkit,
#   (b) carry a comment saying which platform surfaced it and why it is benign,
#   (c) be as narrow as possible (name the frame, do not blanket a whole lib).
# An entry that would hide a defect in src/ is a bug in this file.
#
# There are no active suppressions today — the harness is clean on the dev
# stand (glibc 2.39, valgrind 3.26) and on the ubuntu-24.04 CI runner. The
# template below documents the required shape for the first justified addition;
# it is commented out and suppresses nothing.
#
# {
#     <short-slug-why-benign>
#     Memcheck:Leak
#     match-leak-kinds: reachable
#     ...
#     fun:__libc_<the-exact-libc-frame>
#     # seen on <distro/libc version>: <one line on why this is not our leak>
# }
